Great question — this is exactly where most people misunderstand “agentic AI” 👇

👉 Architecture is NOT challenged in just one phase
👉 It’s an iterative loop across multiple phases, but primarily happens in:

⸻

🧠 🎯 Core Answer

🔥 Main phases where architecture is challenged interactively:

🟡 Phase 3 — Target AWS Architecture (INITIAL DESIGN)

👉 You create the first version

🔴 Phase 4 — Decision Making (HEAVY CHALLENGE)

👉 This is where architecture is questioned deeply

🔴 Phase 5 — Failure Scenario Planning (STRESS TEST)

👉 This is where architecture is broken intentionally

🟢 Phase 13 — Optimization (FINAL REFINEMENT)

👉 This is where architecture is improved and polished

⸻

🧩 How interaction actually happens (real workflow)

🏗️ Phase 3 — You DESIGN

You ask:

Design AWS architecture for this system

👉 Output = Draft architecture

⸻

⚖️ Phase 4 — You CHALLENGE (VERY IMPORTANT)

Now you start pushing:

Why should I use Amazon MQ instead of self-managed RabbitMQ?
What are failure scenarios for RDS vs self-managed PostgreSQL?
What happens if I scale this system?

👉 This is:
Architecture debate phase

⸻

💥 Phase 5 — You BREAK the system

You simulate:

What happens if:
- RabbitMQ crashes?
- RDS fails over?
- EKS node dies?

👉 This reveals:
	•	Weak points
	•	Missing HA
	•	Recovery gaps

💡 This is where your design becomes production-ready

⸻

🔁 Phase 13 — You REFINE

Final step:

Optimize this architecture for:
- cost
- performance
- reliability

What did I miss?

👉 AI now:
	•	Challenges assumptions
	•	Suggests improvements
	•	Finds blind spots

⸻

🔄 REAL “AGENTIC LOOP” (this is the key)

This is what you’re actually doing:

Design → Challenge → Break → Improve → Repeat

👉 NOT:

Design → Done ❌


